title: For Sale:  German WWII MG34 /42 50 Rd Drum – Gurttrommel
postcontent:
For sale, German WWII MG34/42 50 round drum, Gurttrommel, used to hold belted ammunition for the MG34 and MG42 machineguns. Drum is an olive green (not the bluish green post war Yugo color) there are no date, maker or Waffenamt marks visible, but there might possibly be beneath the very thick paint. When I purchased it, this drum came with two other drums and a carrier (these three items are not included or offered for sale), all over painted in the same olive green paint, the carrier was not marked, the other two drums were marked, one was “ddf” and the other had a very faint “WC 41”, almost unreadable due to the extremely heavy paint and apparently light marking strike. The olive green paint, I believe, is Norwegian, as the Norwegians reissued German MG34s and MG42s after WWII and painted them in this color. Beneath the olive green is Panzer grey, and beneath that is the red-brown primer, very commonly used by the Germans during the war. Overall, very good- excellent, used condition, inside of drum shows wear from use, much of the paint is gone, or the red-brown primer is showing, drum is very usable for a working firearm or for a display. Fifty round belt is NOT included. Stamped into the bottom is the characteristic arrow, seen in most all of the German manufactured drums (although some of the earlier ones were painted) Most Yugo drums did not have the arrows, the ones that did, had a very different, more simplistic, less detailed arrow stamped. Drum perfect and recommended for use in semi automatic and fully automatic MG34 and M42 machineguns. Drum can be used with some slight modification, with .308 – 7.62x51 NATO ammunition (I added three layers of thick cardboard to the bottoms of mine to space the .308 out to  properly feed).

Selling for $90.00 plus shipping, US Postal Money Order only, NO Pay Pal, or FTF Frisco, Texas.

Akdal MKA 1919 semi-automatic shotgun is the new product from Turkish company Akdal Arms. This weapon is intended for civilian and security use, and mimics the famous M16 rifle in its layout and placement of most controls. It is remarkably light for its caliber and size, because of extensive use of modern, high strength plastics.

Akdal MKA 1919 semi-automatic shotgun utilizes conventional gas-operated action with annual (ring-type) gas piston, which is located around the support tube that runs below the barrel. Return spring is also located around the same tube, which is concealed by enlarged polymer handguards. Barrel is quick-removable from upper receiver, barrel locking is achieved by tilting locking piece inside the bolt, which engages the barrel extension. Charging handle is attached to the bolt and projects on the right side of the receiver. The upper receiver is manufactured from aluminum alloy; lower receiver, along with pistol grip and shoulder stock, is manufactured as one piece from impact-resistant polymer. Akdal MKA 1919 semi-automatic shotgun utilizes detachable box magazines, each holding 5 rounds; an M16-style bolt stop and bolt release button are incorporated into the lower receiver. Manual safety also duplicates M16-style, being located on the left side of the receiver, above the pistol grip. Standard sights include front post, installed on the M16-style removable base, and a detachable M16A2-style carrying handle with built-in diopter sight.

title: For Sale:  Ruger Redhawk .44 magnum package
postcontent:
Ruger Redhawk, .44 Rem Magnum, 7.5" barrel. It comes with the following: 
* Hogue Monogrip
*Weigand Picatinny no-tap scope mount
*NC Star 2.5x30 eye relief scope with adjustable illuminated reticle 
*Two HKS speed loaders
*Nylon holster rig
*Bulldog speed loader pouches
*leather thumb-break holster
*Ruger box with the original grips and iron sights
*Scope box with instructions, spare battery, and spare rings
*262 rounds of Winchester 240 grain jacketed soft point
*20 rounds of Winchester Partition Gold 250 gr hunting ammunition
*+/- 5 boxes of once fired brass.
This set up has everything you need and nothing you don't and yeah, the NC Star scope does the job, but it was a placeholder until I bought a Leupold or Simmons to replace it. Anyone who knows Ruger's big revolvers knows that Bill Ruger engineered the Redhawk for hand-loaders to use maximum SAAMI pressures on it and the revolver's a rugged beast. I've shot around five boxes and it handles well with manageable recoil. I traded for it and set it up for hunting, used it last season, and now I'm back in university full-time, so I know I'll not have the time in the next two years.
With this package, I value it at $1,000 cash or $1100 trade. Trade options include Sig/Sauer, Walther, Heckler and Koch, Steyr, and CZ pistols only. I have absolutely zero interest in anything Taurus as I already own the only two Taurus models I've ever wanted and no interest in Ruger pistols. I do have some interest in select S&W revolvers or possibly a S&W99.
Anyway, just message me, the worst I can say is "no" and I don't have to sell it, but it's just been gathering dust and with hunting season coming up, I thought someone may be able to put it to proper use.

title: For Sale:  Russian AK74 5.45x39
postcontent:
I have a lightly used Russian Vepr AK74 in 5.45x39 that has barely been fired and it shows!  These are Russian made AK's and have now been banned from importation.  This is by far the best quality and most heavy duty AK that you can buy.  I have both Saigas and Veprs and the Vepr's quality blows Saiga out of the water!  Molot is the Russian factory that produces the RPK Machine guns.  The Molot Vepr AK74 has a 50% thicker receiver than the standard AK as well as a heavy barrel and side scope mount.  

It has a factory threaded barrel and has been tapped for a bullet guide but does not have one installed.  The wood on this is beautiful and the Vepr thumbhole stocks are the best feeling and quality stock of any AK out there.  This comes with both a factory 5 and 10 round magazine.

The 5.45x39 round is the very flat shooting round that the Russians developed the AK74 for and is what they used in Afghanistan.  The Afghanis called it the poison bullet because it was so devastating!  The bullet drop on this is only 6 inches between 100 and 300 yards!

I am asking for 750 dollars for this lightly used Vepr or will trade for a comparable quality AK in 7.62x39.
